                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                      Hadlee to launch   ICC medal  Calcutta: Legendary all-rounder Sir Richard Hadlee will launch the ICC centenary medal on Friday during New Zealand rsquo;s Catch the Spirit week which will be celebrated during the third Test between New Zealand and India at Basin Reserve in Wellington.
  He will present the medals to 10 Wellington-based volunteers at lunch on the first day of the third Test as a recognition of their hard work for the game.  Morgan visit  Dubai: ICC president David Morgan Wednesday paid a visit to Bowral, hometown of Don Bradman, where a museum has been set up commemorating the batsman who finished his Test career with near-impossible average of 99.94. Morgan and his wife Ann visited Bowral as part of the ICC rsquo;s centenary celebrations.  Guards hired  Karachi: The PCB has hired around 100 private bodyguards as part of its comprehensive security plan for the April 22-May 7 one-day series against Australia in Abu Dhabi and Dubai. Apart from the 100 bodyguards, the Dubai police would also press their officers into service to protect the Pakistan and Australian teams.  Miandad pay  Karachi: Javed Miandad has not just managed a triumphant return to the PCB on his own terms but has also got the salary package he had asked for initially. Sources say Miandad has got the Rs one million per month package which is higher than the chief operating officer Saleem Altaf.   Royals rsquo; match   Durban: Rajasthan Royals rsquo; two-match warm-up series against South Africa rsquo;s Twenty20 champions Nashua Cape Cobras has been reduced to a one-off tie. The Royals will play the match on April 11 in Cape Town.   Wayne contract   Durban: Wayne Parnell, aged 19, became the youngest South African cricketer to be awarded central contract by Cricket South Africa Tuesday.   Chowrasia out   New Delhi: S.S.P Chowrasia went down to local golfer Pappan in the second round of the SRF All India Professional Golf Matchplay Championship at Delhi Golf Club on Wednesday. Anura Rohana of Sri Lanka defeated defending champion Arjun Singh.   Paddlers rsquo; stint   New Delhi: Sharath Kamal and Kumaresan Shamini will be among 20 paddlers who will undergo a 25-day training session in China from Thursday as part of their preparation for the 2010 Commonwealth Games. The paddlers, including Subhajit Saha and Poulomi Ghatak, Soumyajit Ghosh and Ankita Das will be training at the National Table Tennis Centre at Zhengding.   Pool meet   Mumbai: Divya Sharma of Haryana pulled off a major upset when he shocked India No.1 Rafat Habib of Railways to reach the knock out phase in the Otters Club All India 9-Ball pool tournament Wednesday.   
